---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Methodology | Constitution Atlas" description="Editorial methodology for the constitutional knowledge base.">
	<section class="page-intro">
		<p class="eyebrow">Methodology</p>
		<h1>How the site should be maintained as it grows.</h1>
		<p class="page-intro__summary">
			Scalability here depends on editorial discipline. Each current-affairs page should identify a constitutional
			question, link to the relevant provisions, cite sources, and carry a clear status label. The site should be
			built around official constitutional text and official institutional records, not around unsourced summaries.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="page-copy prose">
		<h2>Canonical legal text</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Use official constitutional text from India Code and the Legislative Department for Article, Part, and Schedule wording.</li>
			<li>Verify enactment, notification, and commencement details through the eGazette wherever applicable.</li>
			<li>Every interpretive page should point back to one or more concrete constitutional provisions.</li>
		</ul>
		<h2>Judicial and parliamentary sources</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Use the Supreme Court of India portal, eSCR, and the Judgments and Orders portal for official court material.</li>
			<li>Use the Parliament Digital Library for Constituent Assembly Debates, committee reports, and historical debates.</li>
			<li>Use Sansad for current bill status, business papers, parliamentary questions, and committee material.</li>
			<li>Use NJDG only for court statistics and pendency trends, not for doctrinal summaries.</li>
		</ul>
		<h2>Current-affairs sourcing</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Use official institutional sources such as ECI, PIB, and ministry portals for real-time developments and press material.</li>
			<li>Use PRS for secondary legislative analysis and explanatory context, not as a replacement for official text.</li>
			<li>Use journalism for event chronology and context only after the constitutional and institutional sources are identified.</li>
		</ul>
		<h2>Publishing rules</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Every page must disclose sources.</li>
			<li>Every page that explains law, power, or institutions must cite the Constitution text it relies on.</li>
			<li>Every live explainer must define the constitutional issue in plain English.</li>
			<li>Pages should be updated over time rather than replaced by disconnected news posts.</li>
			<li>Official PDFs and portals should be normalized into stable internal content records before publishing.</li>
		</ul>
	</section>
</Layout>
